# Count the number of occurrences of each fund family
fund_family_counts = etf['fund_family'].value_counts()

# Compute the total count and the count for "Others"
total_count = fund_family_counts.sum()
others_count = fund_family_counts[fund_family_counts/total_count < 0.03].sum()

# Replace fund families with less than 3% of the count with "Others"
fund_family_counts = fund_family_counts[fund_family_counts/total_count >= 0.03]
fund_family_counts['Others'] = others_count

# Define a list of colors
colors = ['#FF6666', '#FFCC66', '#66B2FF', '#66FF66', '#CC66FF', '#FFFF66', '#66FFFF']

# Create a pie chart with custom colors
plt.pie(fund_family_counts.values, labels=fund_family_counts.index, colors=colors, autopct='%1.1f%%')
plt.title('Pie chart of fund families in the ETF dataframe')

# Show the plot
plt.show()

etf = etf_merged.dropna()
etf_filtered = etf[etf['fund_symbol'] == 'EWD']
# Filter the data for dates between 2010 and 2021
etf_filtered = etf_filtered[(etf_filtered['price_date'] >= '1/1/2010') & (etf_filtered['price_date'] <= '12/31/2021')]

# Convert the date strings to datetime objects
etf_filtered['price_date'] = pd.to_datetime(etf_filtered['price_date'])

# Create the line chart
plt.plot(etf_filtered['price_date'], etf_filtered['close'])

# Set the x-axis label
plt.xlabel('Date')

# Set the y-axis label
plt.ylabel('Closing Price')

# Set the title of the plot
plt.title('Closing Price vs Date')

# Set the x-axis tick locator to a three-month interval
plt.gca().xaxis.set_major_locator(mdates.MonthLocator(interval=4, bymonthday=1))

# Format the x-axis tick labels to show only the year and month
plt.gca().xaxis.set_major_formatter(mdates.DateFormatter('%Y-%m'))

# Rotate the x-axis tick labels for better readability
plt.xticks(rotation=90)

# Convert the string dates to datetime objects
start_date = datetime.datetime.strptime('1/1/2010', '%m/%d/%Y')
end_date = datetime.datetime.strptime('12/31/2021', '%m/%d/%Y')

# Convert the datetime objects to matplotlib date format
start_date = mdates.date2num(start_date)
end_date = mdates.date2num(end_date)

# Set the limits of the x-axis to show only dates between 2010 and 2021
plt.xlim([start_date, end_date])

# Filter the data for dates between 2010 and 2021
etf_filtered = etf_filtered[(etf_filtered['price_date'] >= '1/1/2010') & (etf_filtered['price_date'] <= '12/31/2021')]

# Convert the date strings to datetime objects
etf_filtered['price_date'] = pd.to_datetime(etf_filtered['price_date'])

# Create the line chart for high and low values
plt.plot(etf_filtered['price_date'], etf_filtered['high'], label='High')
plt.plot(etf_filtered['price_date'], etf_filtered['low'], label='Low')

# Set the x-axis label
plt.xlabel('Date')

# Set the y-axis label
plt.ylabel('Price')

# Set the title of the plot
plt.title('High and Low Prices vs Date')

# Set the x-axis tick locator to a three-month interval
plt.gca().xaxis.set_major_locator(mdates.MonthLocator(interval=3, bymonthday=1))

# Format the x-axis tick labels to show only the year and month
plt.gca().xaxis.set_major_formatter(mdates.DateFormatter('%Y-%m'))

# Rotate the x-axis tick labels for better readability
plt.xticks(rotation=90)

# Convert the string dates to datetime objects
start_date = datetime.datetime.strptime('1/1/2013', '%m/%d/%Y')
end_date = datetime.datetime.strptime('12/31/2021', '%m/%d/%Y')

# Convert the datetime objects to matplotlib date format
start_date = mdates.date2num(start_date)
end_date = mdates.date2num(end_date)

# Set the limits of the x-axis to show only dates between 2010 and 2021
plt.xlim([start_date, end_date])

import xgboost as xgb
from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split
from sklearn.metrics import mean_squared_error

# Convert data into XGBoost DMatrix format
train_data = xgb.DMatrix(X_train, label=y_train)
test_data = xgb.DMatrix(X_test, label=y_test)

# Set XGBoost parameters and train the model
params = {
    'objective': 'reg:squarederror',
    'colsample_bytree': 0.5,
    'learning_rate': 0.05,
    'max_depth': 8,
    'alpha': 10
}

xgboost_model = xgb.train(params, train_data, num_boost_round=100)

# Predict the test data
xgboost_predictions = xgboost_model.predict(test_data)

# Predict the last row of the data and compare to the actual value
last_row = etf_filter[['open', 'high', 'low', 'volume']].tail(1)
last_row_data = xgb.DMatrix(last_row)
predicted_value = xgboost_model.predict(last_row_data)[0]
actual_value = etf_filter['close'].tail(1).values[0]
print('The model predicts the last row or day to be:', predicted_value)
print('The actual value is:', actual_value)

# Calculate  RMSE
xgboost_rmse = mean_squared_error(y_test, xgboost_predictions, squared=False)

# Print RMSE
print('Root Mean Squared Error for xgboost:', xgboost_rmse)

# Calculate the MSE on the test data
xgboost_mse = mean_squared_error(y_test, xgboost_predictions)

# Print the MSE
print('The mean squared error for xgboost:', xgboost_mse)
